{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7fb0eab5-96d5-41ba-88dc-d7effa984189","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Start the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published binary:\n- **Command:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer`\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector launches your process, communicates over stdin/stdout, and shows available tools, resources, and prompts.\n\n**Key tips:**\n\n- **Don't write to stdout** in your server for anything other than MCP JSON-RPC messages — use `stderr` for logging (`Console.Error.WriteLine`), otherwise the Inspector can't parse the stream.\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list and invoke tools interactively, inspecting request/response JSON.\n- If your project needs a build first, run `dotnet build` before connecting, or the startup may be slow on first launch.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"435b4b1d-034b-418c-8a8b-a2280ac9eb98","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore their codebase. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":349},"id":"4ff5932d-75ec-4f39-906a-45a7c95d4b0b","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:50.780Z","parentId":"69a0223f-4532-46d6-a91f-6a412b2c9982"}
